<font color="#FF0000">ON WAKING UP</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug  8 20:56:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
One of the things that enabled me personally to &quot;wake up&quot; and realize that I was in a very coercive and hurtful relationship was having the opportunity to read a lot of the writing I had done while I was in the midst of the relationship.  At the time, I wrote about feeling controlled, inadequate, and paralyzed--but I was so consumed by the relationship (and the person I was with) that I couldn't step back from the immediacy of the pain and realize that I would be better off ending/changing my situation.  I can remember reading one particularly upsetting passage in my journal about three weeks after I had written it, and being shocked at what was happening to me as a person.  I think that having the space to reflect is really important--it's so easy to get caught up in a day-to-day sort of malaise, as I did, and feel lost and powerless over your situation.  Reading my words made me remember the kind of person I wanted to be, the joys I had craved, the ideas that I still had that I had neglected for so long.  People had been telling me and telling me over and over about how I needed to get out of the bad relationship I was in, but only until I allowed myself the space to reflect, examine, and remember, did everything really sink in.  Sometimes it's very hard to find a reflective space in situations that are so controlling and abusive--they can literally consume your identity, energy, everything.   
<p><code>--   (Sabine) </code><p>


